        <hl1>Japanese Ryokan</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Renee Cohen letter on Perri Klass's July 23 travel article offers advice when staying in ryokans in Japan (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: Having returned recently from a walking tour of rural northern Japan, and after seeing  Perri Klass's article on traveling in Japan, ''To See Japan, Try Rail Pass and Ryokan'' (July 23), I offer two suggestions for safety in ryokan.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: Having returned recently from a walking tour of rural northern Japan, and after seeing  Perri Klass's article on traveling in Japan, ''To See Japan, Try Rail Pass and Ryokan'' (July 23), I offer two suggestions for safety in ryokan.</p>
        <p>Take heavy wool socks (the kind you wear with hiking boots) to use as slippers. The ryokan's slippers may not fit you, and it's easier to walk downstairs in heavy socks than in flopping slippers. And take a flashlight to place near your futon while you sleep, in case you get up at night and don't want to trip over others who are sharing your room and sleeping on the floor. As a kindness, take small wrapped candies or sticks of gum, for example, to offer the people who help you and who may give you gifts.</p>
        <p>RENEE COHEN  White Plains</p>
      </block>
